The rate at which the world's economy has been extracting resources
to create products, create infrastructure, and deal with wastes
has been accelerating in recent decades.
% In fact, when the economy grows, the demand for goods and services grows.
% When the demand for goods and services grows, 
% the demand for natural resources grows, too.
Economic growth, by definition, means an increasing demand for goods and services,
which, in turn, means an increasing demand for natural resources.
Figure~\ref{fig:total_material_use} shows the accelerating
rate of extraction of materials from the Earth.
Figure~\ref{fig:per_capita_material_use}
shows the same data on a per-capita basis.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{chapters/ch05-ResourceIntensity/figures/MaterialUseTotalKrausmann2009}
\caption{Total world material use~\cite[Figure~1a]{Krausmann:2009wc}.}
\label{fig:total_material_use}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{chapters/ch05-ResourceIntensity/figures/MaterialUsePerCapitaKrausmann2009}
\caption{World per capita material use~\cite[Figure~1c]{Krausmann:2009wc}.}
\label{fig:per_capita_material_use}
\end{figure}

Figures~\ref{fig:total_material_use} and~\ref{fig:per_capita_material_use} 
show that resource consumption is growing at an ever-increasing rate.
%But is that rate sustainable?
By the ``strong sustainability'' criterion, 
\emph{any} extraction of
construction minerals, ores and industrial minerals, and fossil energy carriers
is unsustainable, because these materials do not regenerate on human timescales.
The fact that we are \emph{increasing} our rate of material extraction 
means that we are running well afoul of strong sustainability.
On the other hand, 
extraction of biomass \emph{can} be sustainable if 
the extraction rate is less than the growth rate.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Weak sustainability}\index{sustainability!weak}
\label{sec:resources_weak_sustainability}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Graedel and Allenby~\cite[p.~17]{Graedel:2010ab} develop a
weak sustainability criterion for 
resource extraction or waste emission rates.
Their approach assumes that human ingenuity 
(either by switching to other materials or by substituting human capital for natural resources)
can overcome resource supply limitations, 
given enough time to react (say, 50 years).
So any rate of consumption of raw materials that preserves supply for 50 years
is deemed ``sustainable.''
The Graedel and Allenby method involves four steps:
%
\begin{enumerate}

  \item Establish the virgin material supply limit, assumed to be
        the amount of resource that can be used per year if the resource is to last 50 years.

  \item Allocate the virgin material supply, 
        often assuming equal per-capita consumption over 50 years.
        
  \item Establish the ``re-capturable'' resource base, often via recycling or mining
        stockpiles and landfills, and allocate to per-capita consumptino over 50 years. 
        The sum of the per-capita virgin material supply rate and the 
        allocated re-capturable resource rate gives the sustainable consumption rate.
        
  \item Compare the current consumption rate and the sustainable consumption rate to assess sustainability
        of current patterns of resource consumption.

\end{enumerate}

Figure~\ref{fig:PercentageOfSustainable} shows the result of applying 
the Graedel and Allenby method 
to two chemical elements (zinc\index{zinc (Zn)} and germanium\index{germanium (Ge)}) and
to worldwide emission of CO$_2$.
This method shows that the world today is far above 
(weak) sustainable levels of consumption and waste emission.
To further underscore the importance of consumption of natural resources to sustainability,
germanium (now being consumed at twice its sustainable rate)
is one of the critical raw materials in Table~\ref{tab:CRMs}.

