\section{Recycling and substitution}
\label{sec:recycling}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Two ways to become more sustainable are recycling and substitution.
Recycling\index{recycling} is a way to extend the usable life
of natural resources and 
reduce rates of resource extraction.
Recycling processes use discarded products as feedstock 
for processes that re-generate usable products. 
Examples include paper recycling to pulp and glass recycling to new containers.
That said, recycling uses energy and other natural resources
for transporting used material to recycling centers, 
processing used material into recycled products, and 
transporting goods to future users. 
For example, paper recycling uses water for cleaning and de-inking processes.
Glass recycling requires high-temperature heat for melting processes.
Whether recycling is, itself, a sustainable means of producing usable products
depends on the strong or weak sustainability of the recycling processes.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Economist Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen proposed a fourth law of thermodynamics, 
stating that complete recycling of matter is impossible~\cite{Georgescu-Roegen:1986aa}.
I.e., material resources are subject to irreversible degradation.
(Georgescu-Roegen was arguing by analogy from the second law of thermodynamics,
which states that all forms of energy are subject to irreversible degradation.)
Later, physicist and economist Robert Ayres correctly
argued that the second law of thermodynamics applies only to energy 
(not to material) and that 
a stable, steady-state recycling system could exist
provided that two conditions are met:
(a) a large stockpile of waste material exists and 
(b) an exogenous source (the sun) supplies energy freely and
at sufficient rate for reprocessing of discarded material~\cite{Ayres:1999}.

The importance of energy to recycling is evident, 
even in a debate about its viability!

\end{mcframe}

Substitution is the process of replacing 
consumption of non-renewable resources 
by consumption of renewable resources. 
Substitution is possible when the two resources in question
are identical or nearly identical.
Examples of substitution in manufacturing processes include:
use of injection-molded plastics instead of coated steel for automobile interior parts
and
use of renewable electricity instead of coal electricity.

Recalling one aspect of Herman Daly's definition of sustainability
(``Nonrenewable resources, such as minerals and fossil fuels, must be used no faster
than renewable substitutes for them can be put into place.''), 
we see that switching
from consuming non-renewable resources 
to consuming renewable resources
is an important aspect of sustainability.

That said, it is important to note limits to substitutability.
At a manufacturing plant, the type of electricity 
(coal electricity\index{electricity!coal} or solar electricity\index{electricity!solar}) 
is immaterial, 
so long as both options are (for the U.S.) 120 V at 60 Hz.
However, at the power station, 
the different sources of electricity are \emph{not} substitute.
Coal-fired Rankine cycle\index{Rankine cycle} power plants
cannot use the sun's energy to make electricity. 
Similarly, a pile of coal is useless 
to a solar photovoltaic\index{solar photovoltaic electricity} farm.


